<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="ff0000"><br>
<center><img src="NEWShead.gif" alt="WWF News Winter 1995"><p>

<BR>
<I>WWF persuades five governments to save the world's largest
wetland</center></I><p>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<img src="uinitial.gif" align=left>ntil last summer, the Pantanal - a rich South American wetland
about the size of England - was threatened by impending construction
of Hidrovia, a massive US$1.3 billion commercial waterway for
sea-going ships that will run through Brazil, Bolivia, Paraguay,
Uruguay, and Argentina and take 30 years to complete. But on 29
August, the Intergovernmental Commission on Hidrovia (CIH), the
international body sponsoring the project, announced it will alter
plans according to demands made by WWF, the International Rivers
Network, Wetlands for the Americas, and a coalition of South American
groups called Rios Vivos.<p>
         A month later, at a briefing at WWF-US in Washington,
DC, Brazilian diplomat and CIH president Marcelo Jardim promised
there would be no engineering work inside the Pantanal, and no
dredging, straightening of river curves, or other construction
<img src="pantanalhd2.gif" alt="Showdown at the Pantanal" align=right>
that could harm the fragile and vital wetland located where Brazil,
Bolivia, and Paraguay meet. He also assured WWF that the blueprints
and studies on Hidrovia's environmental impacts currently under
way will be open to public scrutiny.<p>
        The turnaround was due partly to a united front, with
WWF in Austria, Brazil, Canada, Germany, the Netherlands, the
US, and Venezuelan associate FUDENA creating governmental and
media pressure.<p>
        Modifying Hidrovia so that it does not damage the Pantanal
and other wetlands downstream in the La Plata river basin is not
just a matter of saving wildlife such as endangered jaguars, hyacinth
macaws, and giant otters. Experts estimate that in the first year
of operation, the Pantanal would lose 17 billion cubic metres
of valuable water - enough to supply the freshwater needs of almost
155 million people, or the entire population of Brazil.<p>
        WWF started its campaign with <I>Parana-Paraguay Waterway:
Who Pays the Bill?</I>, an 1994 analysis of the project's economic
and financial feasibility. The report revealed that the proposal
which led to the decision to build Hidrovia was based on a flawed
cost-benefit analysis, which assumed, for instance, that soy bean
production in the Pantanal area would be higher than in the US,
the world soy bean king. In short, Hidrovia, which will require
an additional US$3 billion for maintenance and operating costs,
would be an economic as well as environmental disaster for the
Pantanal region.<p>
        Finally, a WWF video news release and a high-level workshop
in Asunci&oacute;n, Paraguay, in August led to a week of heavy
press coverage on the Hidrovia issue. Following an emergency meeting,
the CIH announced its changes.<p>
        &quot;The waterway is a worthy undertaking as long as
the project is closely watched and handled with great care to
protect the Pantanal,&quot; says Kathryn Fuller, president of
WWF-US.<p>
        Now WWF starts its role as alert watchdog. &quot;It's
a long road until Hidrovia's blueprints are finalized,&quot; says
WWF's wetlands ecologist Gonzalo Castro. &quot;WWF will be monitoring
the environmental impact assessment study and working closely
with the CIH to make sure it keeps its promises to spare this
ecological treasure.&quot; <I>LG</I><p>


</blockquote></blockquote><center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center></body>
