<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="ff0000" border=0>

<br><center><img src="NEWShead2.gif" alt="WWF News Winter 1995"><p>

<img src="standhd.gif" alt="Standing the Test of Time"><br>

</B><I>A 35th anniversary message from the director general </I></center><BR>

<blockquote><blockquote><img src="directorgeneralphoto.jpg"  alt="Picture of the Director General" align=right>
This year, as WWF turns 35, I would like to pay homage to
this organization's founders: Max Nicholson, 93 and still active
in conservation, and the late Sir Julian Huxley and Sir Peter
Scott.<p>
        At a time when the terms &quot;global warming&quot;, and
&quot;biodiversity&quot; didn't even exist, these men had the
foresight to create an organization that would address some of
our planet's most pressing needs - as if they anticipated the
tremendous stress that has come to bear on the earth's natural
systems. <p>
<img src="pandalogoevolved.jpg" alt="Picture of the evolution of the panda logo" align=left> 
Since WWF was founded, the world population has almost
doubled - that's 3 billion more people the world must feed and
shelter. And since I started work on my first WWF field project
25 year ago - to save the Central Indian swamp deer from extinction
- climate change, dying fisheries, and other once unimaginable
environmental problems have become reality.<p>
        WWF has grown and shaped itself to the times to become
the world's largest and most experienced conservation organization.
WWF's panda logo is today the fourth most recognized symbol in
the world - after McDonalds, Shell, and the Christian cross.<p>
        Since 1961, WWF has led and contributed to many important
conservation achievements - from the more than 330 protected areas
it helped to establish, to the creation of the Southern Ocean
Whale Sanctuary in 1994, which means long-term protection for
90% of the world's whales, to its recent success influencing the
European Union and the World Bank to reform national economic
indicators to include the value of natural resources in national
accounts.<p>
        Perhaps one of WWF's most important contributions is to
have introduced environmental education in thousands of schools
around the globe and to have raised public awareness of conservation
from Argentina to Zimbabwe. More and more businesses are recruiting
environmental consultants and environmental law is a growing field.
Management schools now incorporate green issues into their courses,
equating good business with sustainable resource use.<p>
        WWF wants to be so successful that it has no work left
to do. Through its field programme of 617 projects, it builds
local communities' appreciation and ability to practice conservation,
so they can take care of, defend, and benefit from their own natural
resources. The future will show that man and nature are in the
same boat.<p>
<p>
<I>Dr Claude Martin</I><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</blockquote></blockquote><center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
