<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="ff0000"><br>
<center><img src="NEWShead2.gif" alt="WWF News Winter 1995"><p><p>


<img src="projtbar.gif" alt="Project news">
<p>
<img src="hd6.gif" alt="A Princely Arctic Trip"></center>
<BR>
<blockquote><blockquote>HRH The Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh and WWF International
president, put the spotlight on Russian conservation when he made
a five-day tour of the Russian Arctic, where WWF's Russia Programme
Office and Arctic Programme have been working hard to protect
some of the country's most remote and untouched natural areas.
<p>
 <img src="princeinforestphoto.gif" alt="Picture of Prince Philip in the forest" align=left>       
Prince Philip stopped at three WWF conservation sites:
Khatanga and Dickson on Siberia's Taimyr Peninsula, where WWF
helped establish the Great Arctic Reserve in 1993 and the Lena
Delta Reserve in Yakutia.<p>

        In Yakutia, one of Russia's richest republics (due to
oil, gold, diamonds, and uranium), Prince Philip inaugurated the
Nordenskiold-Lena Delta Station, which is jointly funded by WWF-Sweden
and the President of Yakutia's &quot;Diamond Fund&quot;. The station,
named after the Swedish explorer, will play a central role in
the management and monitoring of the reserve.<p>
<img src="shacksphoto.gif" alt="Picture of houses" align=right>
        WWF's Russian work has received another boost: in December,
the Swiss Federal Department of Foreign Affairs granted WWF US$4.2
million, the department's largest conservation grant ever, to
be used in Russia.<p>
        This is Prince Philip's final year as president of WWF
International. Since he took the position in 1981, he has tirelessly
promoted WWF's work, focusing attention on issues that might normally
be bypassed by the media. In the coming months he plans to visit
the Caribbean and Scandinavia on behalf of WWF. <I>LG</I><BR>
<p></blockquote></blockquote>

