<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" vlink="ff0000" link="ff0000"><br><center><img src="NEWShead2.gif" alt="WWF News Winter 1995"><p>

<img src="polbar.gif" alt="Policy"></center><p>
<blockquote><blockquote><img src="hd8.gif" alt="Fighting for Forests Lives">
<BR>

For years the timber trade has argued that it accounts for at
most 20 per cent of the trees taken from the world's forests.
It says the real culprits of forest destruction are the growing
ranks of marginalized people who slash and burn forests to make
way for crops or collect wood for fuel. But WWF's new report <I>Bad
Harvest?</I> (Earthscan, London) finds that it's not the quantity
that counts: the timber trade may log fewer trees, but it causes much 
more damage because it does it only in the world's most species-rich
forests - in search of the biggest <img src="badharvest.jpg" alt="Picture of the book Bad Harvest?" align=right>
and most valuable trees.<p>
        The authors - consultant Nigel Dudley, WWF Forest Programme
head Jean-Paul Jeanrenaud, and Francis Sullivan, leader of WWF's
new <I>Forests for Life</I> campaign - looked at all forest types
with high biodiversity: the forests most important to conservation
and indigenous people for their multitude of plants and animals.
And they found that conditions continue to worsen.<p>
        Since 1993, forest destruction has increased in Bolivia,
Guyana, Cameroon, Latvia, Russia, Laos, and Cambodia. And new
areas are coming under risk - most recently in Papua New Guinea,
Surinam, and Canada.<p>
        To counter the alarming trend, WWF is working to establish
forest reserves and encourage the timber trade to adopt environmentally
friendly logging methods. WWF played a key role in launching the
Forest Stewardship Council, an international body that is pioneering
the independent certification of timber from forests managed under
strict social and environmental standards. The organization has
also set principles for collaborating with indigenous people.
<p>
        &quot;WWF challenges the timber and pulp industries to
follow the lead of companies in the UK, Belgium, Holland, Switzerland,
and the US to work with us and other environmental groups to ensure
their business is based on timber from independently certified,
well-managed forests,&quot; says Jeanrenaud.<p>
        The timber industry could be one of the world's most environmentally
friendly businesses, instead of the nemesis of forests. WWF is
working to make that potential a reality. <p><I>Nigel Dudley</I><p>
<p>

</blockquote></blockquote><center><img src="bargrph2.gif"></center></BODY>
<br>
<br>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center></body>
