<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Unknown Riches</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, June 5, 1996  12:03 PM -->

</HEAD>



<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="ff0000"><br>
<center>



<IMG alt="WWF NEWS" SRC="images/heading.gif"  WIDTH=197 HEIGHT=81 ALIGN=TOP></center><BR>

<center> <hr size=1 width=300 no shade></center>
<center>
<center>
<H2><font color="ff0000">Unknown riches</font></H2>
<center>
<table><tr><td width=400>


Besides their great cultural value, the Kayas are a storehouse of different species, or biodiversity. Scientists estimate that more than half of Kenya's rare plants are found in the Coast Province, and most of that in the largely unstudied Kayas, where ne

w species are still being discovered - their potential uses as food and medicine yet to be identified.

	Botanical surveys have revealed more than 3,000 taxa of plants in the coastal region, of which 30 are probably new to science. Two new species, Thilachium roseomaculatum and Keetia lukei were published in the Kew Bulletin last year.

	Since 1987, WWF researchers have done studies on birds, insects, vegetation diversity, and ethnobotany (under UNESCO's People and Plants Programme). Also last year, two Kayas were designated "globally important bird areas" and Zamarada rufilinearia, a ne

w moth species for Kenya, was identified.

	The Kayas' great biodiversity is the result of several factors, such as genetic isolation, the wide variation in rainfall, and the diverse topography (ranging from sea level to 500-metre-high rolling hills).

	Though scientific and public interest in the Kayas has grown over the last decade, paradoxically, in recent years, they have been under increasing pressure from a growing demand for timber and land for farming, housing, and tourism. A few Kayas, located 

in prime beach areas, have been severely damaged to make way for resort hotels, private beach cottages, and a golf course. And tourism is on the rise: about 500,000 tourists came to the coast for sun and fun last year.

	Two WWF projects have been working since 1986 in collaboration with the National Museums of Kenya (NMK) to record all the coastal flora, lobby for a national conservation strategy to protect the Kayas, and develop education and public awareness programme

s. So far, 23 out of about 60  Kayas and sacred groves have been gazetted as national monuments under Kenya's Antiquities and Monuments Act.

	However, protected-area status is only part of the solution. For as Kaya elder Mzee Ali Kweli points out: "Unlike our children, we know how important the Kayas are and want them to remain intact for future generations. If the Kayas are national monuments

 but are still being grabbed through the local administration, we will lose our livelihood."

	Says WWF project executant Quentin Luke: "By encouraging and supporting the Mijikenda's traditions, WWF in the short term reinforces this indigenous conservation ethic and helps preserve the forests. It's an invaluable focus for general environmental edu

cation. In the long term, the Kayas' survival depends on the success of the awareness programme and on the project-funded review of the existing legislation to give it the necessary strength to face modern-day threats to their existence."
<BR>
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<BR>
<center>
<IMG SRC="images/panda.gif"  WIDTH=83 HEIGHT=89 ALIGN=TOP>
</center>

<BR>
<center>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a>
