<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Cultural Center</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, June 5, 1996  12:02 PM -->

</HEAD>



<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="ff0000"><br>
<center>



<IMG SRC="images/heading.gif"  WIDTH=197 HEIGHT=81 ALIGN=TOP></center><BR>

<center> <hr size=1 width=300 no shade></center>
<center>


<center>
<H2><font color="ff0000">Cultural centre</font></H2>
<table><tr><td width=300>
The Kaya forests are remnants of a patchwork of trees and scrub known in botanic terms as the "Zanzibar-Inhambane regional mosaic of the lowland tropical forest", which linked with the vast rainforests of central and western Africa in prehistoric times.

	 These forest patches sheltered small fortified villages or Kayas, set up by the Mijikenda fleeing from warring Somali Galla enemy groups to the north in the 16th century.

	The Kayas have remained the spiritual centre of each of the nine Mijikenda tribes. Tree felling was forbidden except for selective harvesting of trees and plants for use in the sacred rites. These enduring traditions are the primary reasons the forests still exist.
</td></tr></table>

<BR>

<IMG SRC="images/panda.gif"  WIDTH=83 HEIGHT=89 ALIGN=TOP>
</center>

<BR>
<center>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a>
<center>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>


